{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568197","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568197"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:11:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:11:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19626"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19626","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19626"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.24,0.02,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12397"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97827"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12397"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19626"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"73"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"3360"},{"type":"tags","id":"4957"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"11544"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"29544"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45000"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97827","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97827"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of fever, anorexia, and right upper quadrant pain. She lives in an area of Queensland recently affected by severe flooding, where water and sewage systems have been disrupted. She is currently experiencing homelessness as a result and living on the street. Her medical history includes an appendectomy and cholecystectomy five years ago. She takes no regular medications and previously worked in a commercial pet shop.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 88/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. She has mild jaundice and right upper quadrant tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 135 g/L (115-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite cell count: 6.8 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlanine transferase: 850 U/L (5-40)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EAlkaline phosphatase: 280 U/L (30-120)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ETotal bilirubin: 68 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate: 95 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u003E90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hepatitis A","Leptospirosis","E coli sepsis","Acute Q fever","Acute cholecystitis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features suggestive of acute viral hepatitis A in the context of recent flooding and compromised water supply. The combination of fever, right upper quadrant pain, jaundice, and markedly elevated liver enzymes is characteristic of acute viral hepatitis. Her previous cholecystectomy makes biliary causes less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatitis A\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis given the context of disrupted water and sewage systems following flooding. It is transmitted via the fecal-oral route, often through contaminated water. The incubation period is 15-50 days, and symptoms typically include fever, malaise, anorexia, nausea, and right upper quadrant pain, progressing to jaundice. The marked elevation in transaminases with less prominent rise in alkaline phosphatase is typical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELeptospirosis\u003C/strong\u003E can also occur after flooding and presents with fever and myalgia, but typically causes less severe liver dysfunction and is associated with conjunctival suffusion, muscle tenderness, and renal involvement. While liver enzymes may be elevated, they rarely reach the levels seen in viral hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EE coli sepsis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fever and abdominal pain, but would typically be associated with more systemic signs of sepsis including tachycardia, hypotension, and altered mental status. While liver enzymes may be elevated in sepsis, the pattern and magnitude seen here are more consistent with primary hepatocellular injury rather than the effects of sepsis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute Q fever\u003C/strong\u003E, caused by \u003Cem\u003ECoxiella burnetii\u003C/em\u003E, can cause hepatitis but typically occurs in the context of exposure to livestock or animal products - not typically in commercial pet shops. While it can cause significant hepatitis, the clinical picture usually includes prominent constitutional symptoms and pneumonitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute cholecystitis\u003C/strong\u003E is highly unlikely in this patient as she has had a previous cholecystectomy. Additionally, the pattern of liver enzyme elevation (with very high transaminases) is more consistent with hepatocellular injury rather than biliary obstruction, which would typically show a more prominent elevation in alkaline phosphatase and gamma-glutamyl transferase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConfirmation of Hepatitis A infection requires testing for Hepatitis A IgM antibodies. The public health response is crucial, including notification, contact tracing, and addressing the contaminated water supply to prevent further cases. Post-exposure prophylaxis may be indicated for close contacts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatitis A outbreaks can occur following natural disasters due to contaminated water supplies and disrupted sanitation.","The classic triad of fever, right upper quadrant pain, and jaundice suggests viral hepatitis.","Previous cholecystectomy and appendectomy help narrow the differential diagnosis in acute right upper quadrant pain.","Post-disaster infectious disease surveillance is critical for early outbreak detection."],"references":["Mayer C. Hepatitis A Prevention in Travellers. Australian Family Physician. 2010: 39 (12).  Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/7cc6cdd6-a068-49cb-873e-94cfd2444146/Hepatitis-A.aspx","Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Hepatitis A Outbreaks Linked to Food Sources and Person-to-Person Contact. In: Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [internet] 2024.  Available at: https://www.cdc.gov/hepatitis-a/outbreaks/ongoing/index.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19626"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-09T16:44:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-09T16:47:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12397"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97827"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relatio